      strong Sulina town
      |, whose existence was first documented in 950 by Constantine Porphyrogenitus in his work 
      em “De administrando imperio”
      |, represents the easternmost locality in Romania. The town is situated in the vicinity of the Black Sea, where the alluvia carried by the Danube extend the landline into the sea. Standing proof of this phenomenon, the old lighthouse built in 1802 is now situated in the center of the town and is also considered an important touristic objective.
    p.en Sulina is a very important economic center due to its positioning on the primary axis of the Rhine-Main-Danube Trans-European transport network, as part of the Pan European Transport Corridor VII, connecting the North Sea with the Black Sea. 
    p.en Sulina is a cosmopolitan town, in which customs of numerous nations get intersected. The settlement was a component of the Tsarist Empire, seized from the Turks (1813), then under Austrians (1854), after the Crimean War, under Turks once again, to finally return - with Dobroudgea - as part of Romania in 1878, after the Independence War in 1877.  
    p.en Worth observing is the architectural diversity across the town of Sulina. One can observe the reed-based architecture, these houses being painted in white or blue. Sometimes tiles can be used for rural rooftops, or large eaves, originating from the Mediterranean zone. Alongside this rural architecture one can find urban elements, like storeyed houses, narrow and slender, having commercial stores at the ground floors. After 1856, when the European Danube Commission was founded, the European Commission Palace and the “Jean Bart” house were built). Works on Sulina channel undertaken by the European Danube Commission in 1856, stimulated commercial and transport activities in this area. Thus, along Sulina branch arose a series of villages: Ilganii de Sus, Partizani (Regele Carol I), Vulturu, Gorgova, Crişan (Carmen Silva). 
    p.en Sulina presents many touristic objectives. The Old Lighthouse – hosting the cabinet of Eugeniu Botez, better known by his pen name: Jean Bart. In the same building there is a hall dedicated to the European Danube Commission; the above mentioned “Jean Bart” house; the Water Tower, built with the assistance of the Dutch Queen in 1987; the Greek church St. Nicolas; the old rite Church St. Peter and Paul; the Roman-Catholic St. Nicholas Church – built with the assistance of the Italian community; St. Alexander Church; Sulina Cemetery, where Romanians, Turks, Tartars, Lipovans, Kahols, and also pirates, soldiers, sailors, merchants, etc. were buried; Sulina beach. 
    p.en During World War II, there were over 15,000 inhabitants. After the war, the economic importance of the town decreased, and today there are under 5,000 inhabitants. 
    p.en The town has a culture house, public libraries, schools and restaurants, stores, concentrated on the quays. Also found on the quays is a specialized infrastructure where boats can land. Between the two sides of the town, separated by Sulina channel, one can find boats leaving at specific hours, which facilitate the transport from one side to another. The main activities are: navigation, tourism and fishing. 
    p.en Here can be found accomodation facilities at decent prices, in hotels, pensions, holiday houses, villas, local houses, and a student camp.
